#generate 1000 random no using numpy#plot histogram of generated values #discuss randomnessimport numpy as npimport matplotlib.pyplot as pltrandom_numbers = np.random.uniform(0, 1, 1000)plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))plt.hist(random_numbers, bins=20, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')plt.title('Histogram of 1000 Uniformly Distributed Random Numbers')plt.xlabel('Value')plt.ylabel('Frequency')plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.75)"""Short Discussion on Randomness:1. Variance: Even though the distribution is uniform, the bars are not perfectly    flat. This represents natural variance in smaller sample sizes (1000).2. Law of Large Numbers: If we generated 1,000,000 numbers instead, the    histogram would flatten out significantly.3. Pseudo-Randomness: Computers are deterministic, so these numbers are not    truly random. NumPy uses a Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG) that    creates highly unpredictable sequences using complex math algorithms."""plt.show()